vectorData.altText: 2. Which cell contributes to the myelin sheath surrounding numerous axons?
That's right! Oligodendrocytes form the myelin sheath in CNS. One oligodendrocyte can contribute to the myelin sheath of up to 50 axons.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Oligodendrocytes form the myelin sheath in the CNS: many layers of oligodendrocyte cell membrane wrap around an axon. One oligodendrocyte may contribute to the myelin sheath of up to 50 axons. Many oligodendrocytes are required to myelinate each axon, the number determined by the length of the axon.

Nodes of Ranvier separate oligodendrocytes along the length of an axon, and permit exposure of the axonal membrane to the extracellular fluid. They function to increase the rate of AP conduction along the length of the axon.
